Loss Functions: A mathematical way to measure "how wrong" the model is.
MSE (Mean Squared Error): Used for regression; it squares the difference between predicted and actual values.
Cross-Entropy: Used for classification; it measures the distance between the predicted probability distribution and the actual labels.
Backpropagation: The "engine" of learning. It uses the chain rule from calculus to calculate how much each weight contributed to the total error, moving backward from the output layer to the input layer.
Vanishing/Exploding Gradients:
Vanishing: When gradients become extremely small during backpropagation, causing early layers to stop learning.
Exploding: When gradients become too large, making the model unstable and "overshooting" the optimal values. 
